data.body:
if you set

graphics.IsFullscreen = true;

in the code, the Windows 8 game crashes. We probably need to make this setting do nothing on Windows 8.

On Windows 8 Metro, MonoGame is not firing the MediaPlayer.PlaybackEvent which is used to detect a song has paused or stopped (finished) playing.

Looking at the code that sets up this event in MonoGame (MediaPlayer.cs) we can see that it is using SharpDX's MediaEngine wrapper:

``` C#
        static MediaPlayer()
        {            
            MediaManager.Startup(true);

            using (var factory = new MediaEngineClassFactory())
            {
                var mediaEngine = new MediaEngine(factory, null, MediaEngineCreateflags.Audioonly);
                _mediaEngineEx = mediaEngine.QueryInterface<MediaEngineEx>();
            }

            _mediaEngineEx.PlaybackEvent += MediaEngineExOnPlaybackEvent;            
        }
```

So it is trying to new up an instance of MediaEngine and then hook the PlaybackEvent which is used to route to the XNA MediaPlayer's version of PlaybackEvent that XNA devs can hook into.

This all seems correct.  However, the event doesn't actually fire due to what I consider a quirk of SharpDX's event.

The MediaEngine constructor can also take in a playbackEvent callback.  I assume this maps directly to setting PlaybackEvent internally.

Sure enough, changing the new MediaEngine(...) line in the code snippet above to pass MediaEngineExOnPlaybackEvent as the 4th argument (and then skipping the manual event hook at the bottom) fixes the issue.

There may be more that is needed to understand why += doesn't work, but passing it in the constructor does.

Either way, on Windows 8 Metro the event does not fire today and above is the workaround, if someone could get that into the main branch I would appreciate it.
